ced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Isabel de Sancta-Fide was born in 1160, in Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Adam de Grenville I. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1184, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 24."},"et":{"1160–1184":"1160–1184","1155–1184":"1155–1184","1180–1241":"1180–1241","1184–1241":"1184–1241","1155":"1155","1241":"1241","1184":"1184","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Thame, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hallaton, Leicestershire, England":"Hallaton, Leicestershire, England","Clinton, Thame, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1160–1184":"1160–1184","1155–1184":"1155–1184","1180–1241":"1180–1241","1184–1241":"1184–1241","1155":"1155","1241":"1241","1184":"1184","1160":"1160","1180":"1